<td valign="top" style="padding-right:30px; padding-left:20px;">
<div id="Idea_3528"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/3528-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_3528">Government use of social media should focus more on “small groups of smart people arguing with each other” - Clay Shirky&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/4094-4049">kim</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">4 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">Government use of social media should focus more on “small groups of smart people arguing with each other”, as Clay Shirky (author of Here Comes Everybody) suggests: (http://socialreporter.com/?p=502).  <br/><br/>To achieve this, consider adapting a system such as TransparentDemocracy.org to allow “small groups of smart people” to:<br/><br/>1. Publish proposed decisions.<br/>2. Publish how they recommend the decision be made, and why.<br/>3. See how people and organizations they trust recommend they make the decision.<br/>4. Rate recommendations and comment on proposed decisions.<br/>5. Come up with the best ideas to address the major challenges we face: climate change, pandemics, nuclear proliferation, water scarcity, the Middle East conflict…<br/>6. Prioritize those challenges and approaches to resolving them.<br/><br/><br/>Why important:<br/><br/>Online crowds aren’t always wise.<br/><br/>Clay Shirky (http://socialreporter.com/?p=502):<br/><br/>“I would not be concentrating right now on the kind of large legitimating moves …. precisely because of the hijack model because in a way, even with new tools … tightly interested groups have a way of throwing issues higher up the charts  … I would be worrying instead about how to get good ideas out of small groups.<br/><br/>If you want to know where new interesting useful idea are going to come from, don’t look at crowds and don’t look at individuals, look at small groups of smart people arguing with each other. Historically that’s been a big source of change, whether you are talking about the Invisible College or the French Impressionists. Instead of having Government scale, or social scale initiatives, kind of have your say stuff  …”<br/><br/>See also:<br/><br/>Train skilled community organizers to strengthen our democracy:<br/>http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/dtd/3499-4049<br/><br/>Innovations that increase transparency, participation, and collaboration:<br/>http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/dtd/3505-4049<br/></div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_3528" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_3528', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2255&topicID=3528')">Comments (0)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_3528"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2255">Uncategorized</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=innovations">innovations</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=transparency">transparency</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=participation">participation</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=collaboration">collaboration</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=transparentdemocracy">transparentdemocracy</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_3528"></div>
</div></td>
</tr>
